TiO2 nanoparticles were analyzed in a UV–Vis reflectance spectrometer (DRS), using a UV–Visible-NIR Jasco V-770 spectrometer equipped with a 150 mm diameter integrating sphere coated with Spectralon with 1 nm spectral resolution. DRS was carried out in the 250–2200 nm wavelength range. A Spectralon reference was used to measure the 100% reflectance and internal attenuators were used to determine zero reflectance in order to remove background and noise. The powders were placed on a white substrate, sealed, and mounted on a Teflon sample holder for the DRS measurement. The measured reflectance spectra were subsequently converted to Kubelka–Munk (K–M) absorption factors to evaluate the absorption spectra of the powders. The band-gap was estimated via the Tauc plot FRhνnvs.hν\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
